Virola bombuscaroensis

can be recognized by many pubescence characters. Dendritic trichomes cover its branches, petioles, inflorescence axes, and sometimes along the main veins on the abaxial sides of leaves; the abaxial leaf surface always is marked by stellate, sessile trichomes (Fig. 
4C
); its fruits are covered by ferruginous trichomes that fall very easily to the touch (Fig. 
6C
); the perianth of staminate flowers is densely pubescent on both sides; and the column of filaments has scattered trichomes at the base. Finally, the filament column is straight, not constricted at the apex, and is longer (ca. 1.4 mm) than the anthers (ca. 0.9 mm).
